{
  "doc_id": "51221",
  "text": "However, further technical advances in pH measurement methods are required to create better probes with high spatial and temporal resolution to evaluate pH changes at neural circuit level. Double barreled and concentric microelectrodes can only measure pH at a single point, thus their utility is limited to correlating proton changes with globalized brain activity, for example, during seizures and ischemia [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In contrast, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) is able to simultaneously measure the distribution of protons in the entire brain and is thus able to detect regional variations in pH. For example, presentation of a flashing checkerboard visual stimulus to human subjects induces pH changes localized to the visual cortex [CITATION_3] . However, the spatial and temporal resolutions of MRI are limited tõ 4 mm and~6 s [CITATION_4] , respectively, which are too broad to study pH changes relevant to neurotransmission as these changes occur at spatial and temporal scales of micrometers and milliseconds.",
